  "final_answer": "There are 137 student pairs with very similar study time, defined as daily AI usage differing by <= 0.3 hours, but noticeably different academic outcomes, defined as grade impact differing by >= 2 levels.\n\nExamples:\n- Student 1 vs 57: both used AI 0.8 hours/day, but one reported Slight Decline while the other reported Improved.\n- Student 4 vs 8: both used AI 4.2 hours/day, but one reported Improved and the other Slight Decline.\n- Student 7 vs 76: both used AI 2.0 hours/day, but one reported Slight Decline and the other Improved.\n\nLikely factors explaining the differences:\n- Purpose of use\n  - Students using AI for learning or homework often differed from those using it for coding, writing, or research.\n- AI tool used\n  - Different tools such as ChatGPT, Gemini, Grammarly, and Copilot may support academic work differently.\n- Satisfaction level\n  - Students with higher satisfaction sometimes reported better grade outcomes than those with medium or low satisfaction.\n- Education level\n  - School and university students with the same usage time often had different performance outcomes.\n- Age and maturity\n  - Many pairs differed in age, which may reflect differences in study habits or how effectively they use AI.\n- Contextual factors\n  - City and, in some cases, gender also varied across pairs, suggesting environmental or personal differences may matter.\n\nOverall, similar study time alone does not explain academic performance. How students use AI, which tools they use, and their learning context appear to be more important drivers of whether grades improve or decline.",
